        },
        {
            "text": "To test for addi1onal signatures of natural selec1on, specifically of balancing selec1on, in the IFNL4 region (including the 3' and 5' UTR's; chr19:39736954--39739496) we applied a number of neutrality tests. The HKA [4] test is based on the assump1on that under neutrality divergence is propor1onal to diversity (polymorphism), and both are solely dependent on the muta1on rate. Under selec1on, though, this ra1o is affected: long--term balancing selec1on is expected to result in an enrichment of polymorphisms, while complete (or nearly complete) sweeps of posi1ve selec1on will result in a deficit of polymorphisms (or an excess or subs1tu1ons). To iden1fy such signatures, the HKA test compares the ra1o of diversity to divergence of the test--locus and control--loci.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 217,
                    "end": 220,
                    "text": "[4]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF3"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": ""
        },
        {
            "text": "We used pseudogenes as a proxy for neutrality, and we refer to these regions as our 'control regions' (set of pseudogenes described in Supplementary Note 2). For these regions and our region of interest diversity was calculated as the number of SNPs, and divergence as the number of subs1tu1ons compared to chimpanzee, assessed using the pantro3 lastz alignment from UCSC.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": ""
        },
        {
            "text": "Neutrality tests such as Tajima's D [5] and MWUhigh [6, 7] inves1gate the distribu1on of allele frequencies (the allele frequency spectrum, SFS, Figure X10 ) of our region of interest compared to neutral expecta1ons. The SFS is affected by natural selec1on, with balancing selec1on ohen resul1ng in a skew towards intermediate frequency alleles. Both tests are sensi1ve for such an excess, and thus have power to detect balancing selec1on. Another SFS--based neutrality test, Fay and Wu [8] (FW), is sensi1ve to an excess of high--frequency derived SNPs, and thus detects palerns of recent hard sweeps (complete, classical sweeps from a de novo muta1on).",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 36,
                    "end": 39,
                    "text": "[5]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF4"
