        },
        {
            "text": "Tajima's D and MWUhigh reveal marginal non--significance for European, American, and African popula1ons (Supplementary Table 7) , which could in principle be interpreted as a signature of either weak balancing selec1on or balancing selec1on that maintains alleles at a frequency considerably lower than 50% in the popula1on. Under long--standing balancing selec1on we also expect an excess of diversity due to the long--term maintenance of two or more alleles in the popula1on; this signature is detected by the HKA test. HKA shows no devia1on from neutral expecta1ons (Supplementary Table 7) , and thus no excess of diversity and no evidence of long-term balancing selec1on that predates the expected coalescent 1me under neutrality. Rarely, the excess of intermediate--frequency alleles captured by Tajima's D and MWUhigh can also be the result of an ongoing par1al sweep (reviewed in [12] ) and by selec1on from standing varia1on [13] . So while our results argue against long--term balancing selec1on in Africa and elsewhere, recent balancing selec1on or other selec1ve explana1ons cannot be discarded.",
